Breaking the curse of small datasets and Improving performance of ConvNets

When developing Deep Learning models, one of the biggest challenges is collecting a large dataset.
Thus, in this project, I used different Deep Learning techniques to improve performance of ConvNets when there is only a small number of data files are available.

'Dogs vs. Cats' dataset from Kaggle was used - https://www.kaggle.com/c/dogs-vs-cats/data

The training archive contains 25,000 images of dogs and cats.
Dog pictures are labeled as 1 and cats are labeled as 0. (1 = dog, 0 = cat)

For this project's purpose, only a subset of this dataset was used.

  • 1500 pictures of dogs
    • 1000 for training, 500 for validation, 500 for testing
  • 1500 pictures of cats
    • 1000 for training, 500 for validation, 500 for testing

Retreiving 3000 pictures of dogs and cats from the dataset (1500 imgaes each)

RMSprop for optimizer

What RMSprop does is it keeps an exponentially weighted average of the squares of the derivatives.
This helps damp out the oscillations and is a very effective optimizer

In [5]:
model.compile(optimizer=optimizers.RMSprop(lr=1e-4), loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['acc'])

Data augmentation

Data augmentation is used to increase the diversity of data available for training dataset, without actually collecting new data. Thus, this technique is useful to improve performance for models with smaller dataset.

In [10]:
# Data Augmentation
datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rotation_range=20, width_shift_range=0.1, height_shift_range=0.1,
                            shear_range=0.1, zoom_range=0.1, horizontal_flip=True,
                            fill_mode='nearest')
# shear range for shearing transformation

Add Data Augmentation and Dropout to a previous CNN model to improve performance

Dropout is a regularization method that reduces overfitting and improve the generalization of the model.
During training, some number of layer outputs are randomly "dropped out". So, the model can learn "different path" to the "solution".

In [14]:
model = models.Sequential()
model.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu', input_shape=(150,150,3)))
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2,2)))

model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2,2)))

model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2,2)))
model.add(layers.Conv2D(128, (3,3), activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2,2)))

model.add(layers.Dropout(0.5)) # add droupout
model.add(layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'))

model.summary()

Transfer Learning

Using transfer learning from a pre-trained network can be used to improve its accruacy.
A pre-trained model is a saved network that was previously trained on a large dataset.
For this project, we are going to use transfer learning to customize the pre-trained ImageNet VGG16 model.

Feature extraction

The way feature extracion works is that the pre-trained network is treated as an arbitary feature extractor, which allows the input image to propagate forward, stops at pre-specified layer, and takes the outputs of that layer as features.

In [22]:
import numpy as np
batch_size = 20
datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)

def extract_features(directory, sample_count):
    features = np.zeros(shape=(sample_count, 4, 4, 512))
    labels = np.zeros(shape=(sample_count))
    generator = datagen.flow_from_directory(directory, target_size=(150,150),
                                           batch_size=batch_size, class_mode='binary')
    i = 0
    for inputs_batch, labels_batch in generator:
        # print(inputs_batch.shape) (32, 150, 150, 3)
        # print(labels_batch.shape) (32, )
        
        # feature extraction using conv_base
        features_batch = conv_base.predict(inputs_batch)
        
        features[i * batch_size : (i + 1) * batch_size] = features_batch
        labels[i * batch_size : (i + 1) * batch_size] = labels_batch
        i += 1
        
        if i * batch_size >= sample_count:
            break;
    return features, labels

Freezing layers

Freezing layers prevents its weights from being modified. This technique is often used in transfer learning, where the base model (trained on some other dataset) is frozen.

len(model.trainable_weights) = 4 means the model is only going to train 2 Dense layers, therefore, updating its weight and biasfor each layer.

What else could be added in Transfer Learning?

Fine tuning

The base model has be "fronzen" so that it weights don't get modified.
For fine tuning, we are going to "unfreeze" the last 3 layers of the base model, which are block5_conv1, block5_conv2, block5_conv3.

Why is that only the last 3 layers are going to be fine-tuned?

- This is because earlier layers measure relatively simpler low level features like edges, wherease some later layers measure high level features.
- Transfer learning will make more sense if you suspect that low level features from the pre-trained model could be helpful for learning your task.
- Thus, it doesn't make sense to update weights from earlier layers of pre-trained model, which is why, for this case, only the last 3 layers are going to be trained and "fine-tuned".
- In this way, the model can be designed better to speicifically slove your particualr task.

- Additionally, if more than 3 layers were used for fine-tuning, there will be too many more parameters to train.
- Having too many parameters for small dataset can cause overfitting.
- Therefore, again, only the last few layers are going to be fine-tuned.

Since it is "fine-tuning", it is not desirable to significantly update weights in these layers - block5_conv1, block5_conv2, block5_conv3 thus, the learning rate for RMSprop optimizer has changed to a lower value.

To summarize, fine-tuning consists of unfreezing the entire pre-trained model and re-training on the new data with a very low learning rate.

In [35]:
conv_base.trainable = True
set_trainable = False

for layer in conv_base.layers:
    if layer.name == 'block5_conv1':
        set_trainable = True
    if set_trainable:
        layer.trainable = True
    else:
        layer.trainable = False

Using Exponential Moving Average (EMA) to smoothen the curve

In [37]:
def smooth_curve(points, factor=0.8):
    smoothed_points = []
    for point in points:
        if smooted_points:
            previous = smoothed_points[-1]
            smoothed_points.append(previous * factor + point * (1 - factor))
        else:
            smoothed_points.append(point)
    return smoothed_points

Conclusion

When dealing with small datasets for Deep Learning development, it could lead to overfitting and failure in generalization of the model.

In this project, I covered a few most commonly used techniques to tackle such issues of Deep Learning.
Data Augmentation, Transfer Learning, Feature Extraction, Fine Tuning techniques can be used to "break the curse of small datasets", also Dropout regularization can prevent overfitting.

layer_names = []
for layer in model.layers[:8]:
    layer_names.append(layer.name)
    
images_per_row = 16

for layer_name, layer_activation in zip(layer_names, activations):
    n_features = layer_activation.shape[-1]
    print("Number of Channels: " + str(n_features))
    
    size = layer_activation.shape[1]
    print("Size: " + str(size))
    
    n_cols = n_features // images_per_row
    display_grid = np.zeros((n_cols * size, images_per_row * size))
    
    for col in range(n_cols):
        for row in range(images_per_row):
            channel_image = layer_activation[0,:,:,
                                             col * images_per_row + row]
            channel_image -= channel_image.mean()
            channel_image /= channel_image.std()
            channel_image *= 64
            channel_image += 128
            channel_image = np.clip(channel_image, 0, 255).astype('uint8')
            
            display_grid[col * size : (col + 1) * size,
                        row * size : (row + 1) * size] = channel_image
        
        scale = 1. / size
    plt.figure(figsize=(scale * display_grid.shape[1],
                           scale * display_grid.shape[0]))
    plt.title(layer_name)
    plt.grid(False)
    plt.imshow(display_grid, aspect='auto', cmap='viridis')
    plt.show()

Understanding what each layer in ConvNets do

The first few layers show various edge tections. Also, at that stage, the acivations are still retainig almost all of the information present in the image.

Then, the activations become increasingly abstract and less visually interpretable, which shows that the netwrok has filtered out irrelevant information. Later layers focus on the specific visual appearance (= more useful information for classfication) of the given image.

There are more black feature maps as the depth of the layer increases. This means that the pattern encoded by the filter was not present in the input image.

egyptian_cat_output = model.output[:, 285]

last_conv_layer = model.get_layer('block5_conv3')
# block5_conv3 layer is the last layer of the VGG16 

grads = K.gradients(egyptian_cat_output, last_conv_layer.output)[0]
# graident of 'egyptian_cat_output' with regard to the output feature map

pooled_grads = K.mean(grads, axis=(0, 1, 2))
iterate = K.function([model.input], [pooled_grads, last_conv_layer.output[0]])

pooled_grads_value, conv_layer_output_value = iterate([img_tensor])

for i in range(512):
    conv_layer_output_value[:, :, i] *= pooled_grads_value[i]
heatmap = np.mean(conv_layer_output_value, axis=-1)

heatmap = np.maximum(heatmap, 0)
heatmap /= np.max(heatmap)
plt.matshow(heatmap)

import cv2
def deprocess_image(image):
    image -= image.mean()
    image /= (image.std() + 1e-5)
    image *= 0.1
    
    image += 0.5
    image = np.clip(image, 0, 1)

    # convert to RGB array
    image *= 255
    image = np.clip(image, 0, 255).astype('uint8')
    return image

img = cv2.imread(img_path)
